  "transliteration": "tat kṣhetraṁ yach cha yādṛik cha yad-vikāri yataśh cha yat\nsa cha yo yat-prabhāvaśh cha tat samāsena me śhṛiṇu",
  "translation": "Now hear briefly about the field, its nature, its transformations, and its source.",
  "purport": `
    <p><strong>1. Structured Deconstruction of Reality:</strong> Krishna does not leave Arjuna with abstract philosophical ideas; instead, He begins a systematic breakdown of existence. By dividing the ‘field’ into its nature, its modifications, and its origin, He introduces a methodological approach to self-inquiry. This reflects that spiritual knowledge is not meant to be vague or mystical in an inaccessible way, but rather something that can be examined, understood, and internalized through careful observation and reasoning. Such structuring transforms spirituality from blind belief into a disciplined exploration of truth.</p>

    <p><strong>2. Impermanence as a Defining Characteristic:</strong> The emphasis on ‘vikāra’ (modifications) highlights that everything within the field is subject to continuous change. The body grows, ages, and deteriorates; the mind constantly shifts between thoughts and emotions; circumstances evolve beyond control. This constant flux is not an exception but the very nature of the field. Recognizing this deeply dismantles attachment, because attachment thrives on the illusion of permanence. When one sees clearly that change is inevitable, clinging begins to lose its grip.</p>

    <p><strong>3. Inquiry into Origin and Causation:</strong> Krishna’s mention of the source of the field pushes Arjuna toward a deeper philosophical investigation. It is not enough to observe what exists; one must question why and how it exists. This inquiry leads the mind beyond surface-level perception into metaphysical understanding. It opens the door to realizing that behind the changing field lies an unchanging reality, which is not produced but is the very ground of existence itself.</p>

    <p><strong>Conclusion:</strong> This verse acts as a gateway into analytical spirituality, where the seeker is encouraged to examine life not emotionally but structurally. It teaches that clarity emerges when one studies reality in terms of its composition, its ever-changing nature, and its ultimate source. Such an approach gradually dissolves confusion, because instead of reacting to experiences, the individual begins to understand their mechanics. This shift from reaction to observation is the beginning of true wisdom, where life is no longer chaotic but comprehensible, and the seeker becomes capable of perceiving deeper truths beyond surface appearances.</p>
  `
